deck_excerpt: A good mid-range deck to get you started in master duel.
deck_description: Although this is a combo heavy deck, once you understand it's main strategy everything else will come naturally. Your opening plays will ideally start with you using Swirl Slime in the hand with Necro Slime to summon D'Arc, getting at least one other monster on the field (usually by normal summoning a Kepler for a search or a Lamia so you potentially get two uses out of her ideally), using Necro Slime in the gy to bring out Genghis, then linking away D'Arc and your other monster that isn't Genghis to bring out Gilgamesh, set your scales and use Genghis' effect to bring back your D'Arc. After this opening the deck can go in a few directions depending on what you have left in your hand or gy. Brining out Siegfried should be a priority since it's an easy spell/trap negate without an extra cost. Ghost is best used to send back your banished Necro Slimes to the gy by using it for Necro Slime's fusion, he's also a tuner.

deck_excerpt: A theorycraft for running the Brave engine in Inzektor despite a bit of anti-synergy.
deck_description: This is an idea I had when opening packs of Grand Creators for some Inzektor stuff.  The Adventure engine is very commonly used in many decks like Prank-kids and PK to insulate combo lines against potential interaction from the opponent, as well as extending combos if no such interaction exists or baiting said interaction if the opponent stops the engine from resolving.  This would hugely benefit Inzektor, which has historically died very hard at certain choke points especially with bad hands and prior to Zektrike Kou-Ou hasn't had very powerful ways to extend through said choke points.  Even if you draw some of the soft garnets in the Brave engine, like Dracoback or Griffon Rider, it's not actually a bad thing.  Dracoback has minor equip synergy with the Inzektors provided you have a way to pop it, and Griffon rider at the very least is a free body to Link with. The problem, however, is the downside inherent in the Adventure engine:  during the turn you resolve Rite of Aramiser, you can't activate the effects of normal summoned monsters.  This is a big problem, considering so many of the classic Inzektor routes revolve around that first normal summon, not to mention the extra normal summon you get from Beetrooper Armor Horn.  Because of this I thought it was a bit disappointing that such anti-synergy exists, considering how much the deck would love to run the engine.  But then I thought maybe they still can.  Yes, there are some hands where you cannot use the brave engine and thus it's more or less dead.  But thanks to Zektrike, there are a lot of 3 or 4 card hands that could allow you to resolve the engine and play through your turn without relying on your Dragonfly or Centepede to be normal summoned, at least not to get effects from doing so.  Additionally, there are many hands where you draw the soft garnets to act as situational extenders.  Heck, there's no penalty for activating Enchantress, so even if your hand can't resolve the brave engine, perhaps just activating Enchantress is enough to make an antsy player burn their Ash.   The brave engine also makes it so even if your hand is utter crap, with no real way to get the Inzektor flow going, just opening Rite or Enchantress is enough to let you end on something. I'm no expert in Inzektors or how well this would work out in practice, but I think it's at least worth testing out.  It's certainly a lot more interesting of a concept than simply replacing the 7 Adventure engine cards with 2 Crossout Designator + 1 of stuff I want to hate on, at least, and I think it should be less bricky too.  What are your thoughts on the concept and the deck ratios?

deck_excerpt: I use only virtual world monsters for main deck and give myself plenty of extra deck combos.
deck_description: I like to play vw with as many options and effects as I can and the best ones are in the extra deck.  It is pure vw and the best play is to:     Get a vw name on the field preferably spell or trap (has to be face up)  If possible get 1 chuche and 2 qinglong  to graveyard and 1 of each on the field (to be able to cycle cards from gy to banish to deck)  Now you can go for the caliga crystal wing if you have a spell or trap in hand to set and can make 2 level 6 (you can also use stardust charge warrior a L6 tuner) one tuner one not tuner as well as 2 level 3 for synchro  Synchro summon tzolkin to emz in defense set a face down spell/trap and special summon crystal wing  Synchro summon muddy mud dragon and use it's effect and fusion summon with muddy mud and tzolkin to make caliga and set him in defense     Or my preferred combo if possible to synchro xx-saber gottams use his effect synchro summon cloud castle use his effect to special summon back gottams and then xyz into true king  Get a vw name on the field preferably spell or trap (has to be face up)  If possible get 1 chuche and 2 qinglong  to graveyard and 1 of each on the field (to be able to cycle cards from gy to banish to deck)  You need a tuner and an earth monster that equal level 9 to synchro summon gottams and once you do you immediately activate his effect and destroy himself  Next you need a tuner and non tuner for a level 9 synchro summon and summon cloudcastle and use it's effect to special summon back gottams  From there you can xyz true king and effectively stop most decks.

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes Master Duel with Accesscode Talker
deck_description:
• Focus on bring 2 level 8 monsters to the field
    • You can do this by using the effect of the Sage with the Eyes of Blue, Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon and Nebula Dragon
  • Summon Number 97: Draglubion, use its effect to summon Number 92: Heart-eartH Dragon using Number 100: Numeron Dragon as material
    • Number 92: Heart-eartH Dragon wipes whatever the opponent built on its turn
    • After this, Number 97: Draglubion can summon Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy and prevents the enemy to activate a spell once per turn
  • Summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon and use its rank-up combo to clean the opponent field
    • After summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Dragon, use it to summon Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon and destroy a face-up card on the opponent field
    • After use the effect of Galaxy-Eyes Full Armor Photon Dragon, use it to summon Galaxy-Eyes Cipher Blade Dragon to destroy another card on the opponent field
  • Use Skill Drain if your opponent's deck runs on top of monster effects. Remember that Blue-Eyes it's a boss monster itself.
  • If your opponent have a solid field and if you have battle in your turn with a Xyz Monster, summon Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder to wipe everything at the end of the turn
  • If you have used at least 3 spells, consider using the Accesscode Talker combo
    • First, summon Cryston Halqifibrax. Use its effect to summon a spellcaster turner monster (can be the Sage with Eyes of Blue or the Effect Veiler).
    • Summon Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians and use its effect to summon back the spellscaster monster you've summoned with Cryston Halqifibrax
    • Summon Accesscode Talker tributing Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians, then use its effect targeting Selene on the graveyard to get 5300 of attack power. Also, use its effect to destroy one card your opponent controls.

deck_excerpt: Masked HERO deck themed around having every single member in it, inspired by Kamen Rider.
deck_description: Masked HERO deck aimed in having every single one of its members, since I'm a Kamen  Rider fan. It wasn't made with competitive play fully in mind so it will most likely struggle against the top meta decks. It was also done in Master Duel specifically so keep it in mind regarding some cards like Maxx C, you might want to change them depending on how and where you're using this.  That being said, some cards were added in the extra deck to make it more survivable like Isolde, Sunrise and Absolute Zero. One of the best combos is to summon Absolute Zero (preferably with Liquid Soldier as one of its materials to activate its effect too) and then Mask Change it to Masked HERO Acid. This will trigger Absolute Zero's Raigeki effect and Acid's Harpie's Feather Duster effect, wiping the opponent's field (provided you're able to do it without negation, of course).  • Don't be afraid to send Shadow Mist to the graveyard, but do be careful when you activate her effect in there. Do not special summon her from the GY on the same turn because you can only activate one effect per turn.  • If you ever use Liquid Soldier's effect to draw 2 cards and have to discard one, and you end up with both a "Change" card and "Mask Charge", discard the "Change" card, you'll be able to recover it immediately with Mask Charge (provided you also have a HERO in the GY).  • Contrast HERO Chaos is the ace of the Masked Heroes and you'll want it as soon as possible.  Any comments for improvements to it are welcome, but keep in mind the theme of the deck is to have every Masked HERO in it in tribute to Kamen Rider.

deck_excerpt: For those who like that Synchro good stuff.
deck_description:
This is a basic synchron deck that I made in Master Duel. I don't play much ranked so I can't tell you how well this would do, but it is a fun deck to play if you like vomiting Synchros on to the field.  There are some cards that I plan to remove once I find cards powerful enough to replace them, which i'll go over now.   - Righty Driver & Lefty Driver

While these two cards have let me do some crazy stuff, this deck is already reliant on Normal Summons and i'm only able to go into a level 3 or 4 with them.In contrast, i'm able to do some much more crazy stuff with Synchron carrier and Junk Synchron. I'll probably add some handtraps to make the deck more ranked friendly, as the only negate that i really go into is Crystal Wing.

  - Quillbolt Hedgehog

I only really added this card because I had one more spot to fill.

  - Goblindbergh

If I can't find a card that procs on Special Summon then I'll definitely replace it.

  - Crystron Halqifibrax 

While i have loads of nostalgia for this card, i have to admit that i does kind of interfere with my deck.

  - Clear Wing Synchro Dragon

I had this card in the deck before i acquired Crystal Wing and didn't bother to find anything to replace it.

  That's it for now, when i find the cards i'm looking for I'll post an updated list. Any feedback would be appreciated.

deck_excerpt: A fun deck that I used to climb to Platinum on Master Duel* and one I also use in real life
deck_description: As the name implies, this deck focuses on being able to turbo out Toadally Awesome turn 1 and contains lots of rank 4s that can be special summoned to achieve this. Ideally on turn 1 you want to bring out Bahamut Shark to detach a material and then summon Toadally Awesome. Having Defender of the Ice Barrier with another Ice Barrier monster on field is also great since it stops your opponent from declaring an attack (as long as their monsters have attack greater than 1600). On turn 2 you will want to summon out either Trishula Zero Dragon of the Ice Barrier or regular Trishula to remove cards with its' non-targeting banishing effect. Usually, if my opponent has 3 or more cards I will try to summon Zero Dragon, and if they have only one card on the field I will summon out regular Trishula so I can also banish cards from their hand and graveyard too.  If you manage to draw Gozen Match on turn one then this is a great time to summon Number 4: Stealth Kragen from the Extra deck as it changes all monsters to the water Attribute. If your opponent does not play any water monsters this is especially effective, as they will simply be locked into the one monster that you have changed into water with Steatlh Kragen plus the effect of Gozen Match.  *I used a modified version of this deck to climb to Platinum in Master Duel. Since Toadally Awesome is limited to one on Master Duel I substitute the second Toad with Number 47: Nightmare Shark. I also cut 1 Prior of the Ice Barrier, Salvage and Upstart Goblin for 3 Maxx "C" since the extra draw power is absolutely incredible in this deck. If you can find other cards that consistently give you draw power I heavily recommend that you use them in this deck as they help it greatly, both in real life and in Master Duel.

deck_excerpt: Witchcrafter core with Spellbook engine
deck_description: A witchcrafter spellbook deck I play in master duel. It can comfortably achieve platinum rank in this current state. The spellbook engine will allow you to trade your normal summon for: draw power (knowledge), attack points (power), or non-destruction non-targeting removal (fate). It is also a great way to bait out interruptions so you can get your witchcrafter boss monsters out. Because the spellbook engine steals your normal summon, I run 3 copies of unveiling and 3 copies of reasoning.

deck_excerpt: Use Darklord Nurse Reficule or Bad Reaction to Simochi to "heal" your opponent
deck_description:
1. Gameplan:

    1. Play Darklord Nurse Reficule or Bad Reaction to Simochi
    2. Use Gift Card, Tri-and-Guess, The Paths of Destiny and Trap Trick to "heal" your opponent

    Tips:

    • Make sure you trigger Bad Reaction to Simochi LAST so it resolves before the rest of your traps. If you trigger it first then your heals will go off first without Simochi's effect on the board.
    • Extra deck can have anything as long as it has 15 fusion cards.
    • For Tri-And-Guess: Unless you know your opponent is playing synchro monsters, pick XYZ because most opponents run at least one.
    • Remember that Darklord Ixchel can target Banishment of the Darklord in addition to Nurse and another Ixchel

deck_description: So, i was inspired to build this after...     A: Finding out how stupid Necrovalley is against Eldlich  and B: Gren Maju got gutted by the recent banlist     This is a control deck strategy, and the extra deck is honestly optional if i'm being honest if you're planning to just run kaijus and no Danger! monsters for a casual deck build. I'm still figuring out the side deck currently, so i'll update this page when i've got a better idea of what cards would be good to side into this.     EDIT 1: Decided to lean more into the sort of level 8 kit normally seen in Gren Maju.     EDIT 2: Some people on YGO Omega Discord server pointed me to some cards that would help get out the rank 8 monsters more consistently, so those changes have been made. Dogwood is still in the extra deck because "lmao, life point farming."     EDIT 3: I'm throwing a full blown Danger package into the side deck because this was getting curb stomped by the Altergeist bot in YGO Omega.

deck_excerpt: I just reached Platinium 1 with this deck, here's the deck list.
deck_description: I just reached Platinium 1 with this deck, here's the deck list. 10 handtraps, 10 draw power, 20 other cards, balanced, as all things should be. Blind 2nd, use handtraps and spell cards to outplay opponents.   Reasons for NOT playing some of commonly played cards: Infinite impermanence: Too many effect negations already, effect veiler, fobidden chalice, widow anchor. Raigeki, lightning storm: Most monsters have floating effect or proections nowdays, these cards might sometimes brick you. Pot of Avarice: This card sometimes brick, you cannot use it turn one. Ghost belle, Droll & lock bird, Ghost ogre, Gamma: Not generic enough, sometimes brick. Call by the grave & Shark Cannon & Crossout Designator: Not all decks use monsters in graveyard, sometimes brick. Upstar goblin: Chicken's game is better, sky strikers have a hard time OTKing opponent with more than 8K LP,  Accesscode & 2 sky striker monsters can only output 8K damage. Kaiser Colussum & There can only be one: Mostly useless if not going first. Foolish Brial Goods & Metalfoe Fusion & Toon table of content: Bricks more than it helps. Knightmare phoneix: cannot use it to out skill drain, imperial order is at 1 and rarely seen, not worth it. Harpie feather duster, other S&T removal: If Eldlich didn't open skill drain and imperial order, these are not really needed.   Reasons for playing some of the cards: 2 Nibiru: Not 3 by reducing chances of bricking, but high enough for opening & maxx c into it. 2 Veiler: Not 3 because it might brick, need at least 2 for accesscode play. Borrelsword: To beat off some "unaffected by card effects" boss monsters. 2 Pot of desires: Not 3 because, A, you don't want desires into desires, B, you can't really use 2 since you only have 40 cards in your deck. Eagle Booster: Good for preventing OTKed by opponent, use it on accesscode and win next turn. Imperial iron wall: Hurt most decks and help yourself. Drytron: cannot use eva to +2. Tri-brigade: no banishing to summon & link-4 removal. Gren-maju: dead. VW: shenshen effect useless. Eldlich: cannot go +1 off of traps in grave. Cyber dragon: cannot fusion summon. Invoked Shadoll: invoked summon play got hindered.  Generic: Stops accesscode, callby the grave and crossout designator, DD crow, Most Pots. With Multirole & Impeiral iron wall, you can loop your spells infinitely, gaining unfair advantage. You can also get rid of it with multirole if it hinders you.

deck_excerpt: One Tamer Boi summons massive value, Gladiator Beast estravaganza
deck_description: A more Endurance oriented variant of Gladiator Beast its game plan is to Summon GB Tamer Editor(due to the Higher stared monster in this variant summoning themselves out of your hand this is incredibly easy) then summon either GB Heralkinos or GB Domitianus depending on your current hand size and your opponent's deck structure to lock then out or shut them down and prevent their combo plays. After that you focus on maintaining a large hand size by looping either GB Equeste or GB Darius for more advantage and GB Sagitarii to contsantly keep GB Heralkinos active, slowly depriving your opponent of their plays and forcing them to basically lose value on any of their plays. And when facing a more control oriented or SS negation deck you can side deck into a Paleo/ GB stradegy removing the Value engine of GB Sag and a copy of Darius alongside some of the Spell support for GB.

deck_excerpt: Discussion about one of my favorite decks since I started playing Yu-gi-oh!
deck_description: My goal is to discuss why you should remember Mathmech as a Salamangreat-style Cyberse midrange deck and not a Crusadia-style OTK deck just because you have the Final Sigma win button. Many of the games have a grind game of more than 5 turns so much more important than trying to OTK at all costs with this deck is to exchange resources efficiently which is very easy to do thanks to the absurd cards called Mathmech Superfactorial and Laplacian that are a potential -3 to even -4 for the opponent counting the Mathmech Diameter omni negate. Not to mention that archetype XYZ monsters are excellent and even a little stolen when reading for the first time, Alembertian being a Searcher and Extender and Laplacian a Trishula that can be given on the opponent's turn. An interesting point about Mathmech's Extra Deck monsters is that they are generic and can be used in almost any deck. I myself am sure that someday there will be a deck to abuse Alembertian absurd effects when made with 3 materials or 4 materials. /////////////////////////////////////////                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Decklist picks: The Mathmech archetype cards such as Synchro level 8, Equip's spell and Reborn's spell and Trap which is a pop don't do much for the deck and therefore are not part of the decklist. Generic Cyberse support like Lady Debug and Cynet Mining are cards that take up consistency card slots and hand traps so in the end they don't do much for deck strategy. Cynet Mining doesn't have good discards in the deck and you don't need these cards to play Mathmech after all. ///////////////////////////////////////// Recommended cards: Mathmech's deck in the TCG enters this February format with a lot more consistency issues because of the Pot of Desires limitation and one card that can help the deck is Triple Tactics Talents which is a very versatile card. Another card that I highly recommend using in the deck is Topologic Zeroboros because it's very easy to trigger its effect and clear the opponent's field by going second. /////////////////////////////////////////Combos: This topic is not really a tutorial on how to play each specific hand, but plays I made with a random hand that I opened playing with the deck. It's a nice way to show the deck's proposal from where it wants to go, considering how you would start your moves and the play lines chosen. The important thing is to understand that this is a deck that does not tolerate errors during gameplay, so you should always be aware of the most efficient way to play. These examples that I show you along with the technoplay tips that I talk about after these combos are enough to get you started playing Mathmech. As you can see these combos are narrations of how I played with a certain hand and how I behaved after taking interactions like hand traps and from the opponent's established fields as well. From the End Board you can see that the objective is to pass with the Superfactorial trap along with 3 Mathmech Monsters in the GY with different names including the Diameter which turns the Xyz Mathmech into an omni negate as well. For this we use the Link Disciple + Link Devotee combo to access Link-2 Wicckid that adds the Diameter/Nabla needed to make the Alembertian that adds the Trap Superfactorial at the same time that it finishes the necessary names in the gy. //////////////////////////////////////////// Combo 1: Diameter + Sigma Sigma eff SS from HAND and NS Diameter RANK-4 Alembertian(have 1 Negate) and eff Add Addition and SS Sigma SYNCHRO 12 Final Sigma ///////////////////////////////////////////// Technoplay cards of Main Deck: Balancer Lord + any Mathmech is a full combo with Nabla tribute Linguriboh bringing the Diameter from the deck to make Alembert and add the Superfactorial and pass. You always use the Balancer Lord effect from Extra Normal Summon and save to use only the normal summons of good cards that are the basics of the deck save the Normal Summons for the right cards. Diameter allows your Mathmech boss monsters to be omni negate to interact with the opponent or negate cards like Nibiru on your turn. Whenever you open it with Diameter you want to throw a monster in the gy to take advantage of its Normal Summon. So much so that even if you draw from Balancer Lord + Diameter, you doing this play do very well. However you have to analyze if your hand is too weak for interactions because in that case a negate in the Mathmech Diameter makes your turn end. You have to remember that Alembertian is guaranteed to search for negate so it is always safe to go straight to it with Diameter. Mathmech Nabla is a fundamental piece to access the missing monster to make the Superfactorial alive in the opponent's turn, especially the Diameter but it can be Sigma if you already have access to the Diameter. If you open from Nabla and Diameter but you can't have a monster in the GY, the best thing is to use Nabla from NS and use eff SS Diameter from Deck and keep the Diameter in hand as Follow Up. If you can use Multiplication/Nabla as Xyz material on your next turn if you Tribute Xyz with the effect of Nabla or Alembertian it trigger eff to double ATK/Monster can make two attacks which is cool if the monster you make is Accesscode for example. Important to know the right choices of how to start hand summons, see the details to have plays after interactions mainly going second. When you open with RANK-4 Alembertian play and Extender you can start adding a Superfactorial and then go to play Link Disciple and Devotee and Wicckid combo. But this is not an orthodox play and it might be good to first go to Wicckid turbo play to gain access to Diameter to ensure Alembertian will resolve and add Superfactorial. Primary Follow Up is adding Diameter and secondary is adding Nabla/Sigma. Cool is that if you already open with Superfactorial, use Alembertian to add Extenders or Nabla to access Diameter and try to generate an advantage with Link Disciple and Link Devotee moves etc. If you can stop the opponent without having to use the Superfactorial, it's very good to leave it to use it only on your turn because in addition to the mini Trishula you get right at the beginning of the Diameter's negate turn to play safe your turn. You only activate on his turn with him doing nothing that threatens you if he sets a trap on the same column as the Superfactorial because it will most likely be an Infinite Impermanence. Many times you want to play Accesscode Turbo and even then you don't have a chance to OTK it and so using two Superfactorial and two Laplacian is essential. It's important to understand that this is not an OTK deck so using the second trap in matches plus grind game is fundamental, looking at the gamestate and predicting the best move is essential in decks that are based on trading resources and for everything I've played with this deck you always take the game to a simplified gamestate. Always try to play around Forbidden Droplet when you have I:P Masquerena + Superfactorial on the field because first you must use I:P Masquerena eff and if he negates with Droplets you will still have the Superfactorial summon Laplacian. If you take Called By The Grave in the Superfactorial eff on one of the 3 targets in the gy you will still be able to summon the other two targets and do the Alembertian at least to add a Follow Up and if you have the Diameter as material have an omni negate also. Only if the opponent banishes at least 2 targets from the Superfactorial that it doesn't resolve. Parallel eXceed does not trigger eff if MASTER DUEL game button is Off. If you are facing a deck that uses Skill Drain, summon Parallel eXceed in Attack Position because if your opponent uses Skill Drain the eXceed returns to 2k atk and at least you will have a monster with great attack to try to survive until you take the Skill Drain that can be done with even Accesscode using effect and banishing itself from the field as cost. Of the Deck Extenders: Addition, Subtraction and Mathmech Sigma you should pay attention to the card details that first all of them lock you from Special Summoning Cyberse monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn. Second that Sigma is the best extender of the 3 because it is searchable by Wicckid since it is Tuner and being able to come back from GY has the detail of being banned when leaving the field so the only way to not have it banned is to use it as xyz material but it doesn't make much difference to have him banned for his turn 1 combo to pass. Addition and Subtraction cannot declare an attack in the turn that are Special Summoned by their own effect and they can target opponent's monsters whatever better the deck to go second and break the field. Against Decks Blind Second = This deck doesn't care about many of the cards used to break the field. For example Lightning Storm on monster doesn't affect the deck at all because of Wicckid and Laplacian and Dark Ruler No More at best takes the interaction from I:P Masquerena only. Evenly Matched is another card that the deck handles easily. The best blind second card against Mathmech is the Forbidden Droplet. ///////////////////////////////////////////// Technoplay cards of Extra Deck: Laplacian doesn't destroy the cards but sends them to the GY so you can take spells/traps out of the field on the protection of Heavenly Sky or the Golden Lord that came back from the GY by its own effect. Alembertian on the Following turn is usually to add extenders to kill the opponent whether Sigma or Nabla bring Multiplication from the deck and do FINAL SIGMA or Accesscode Talker Turbo or continue controlling the game with Superfactorial. *(Don't FORGET that LINK DEVOTEE has a MANDATORY Eff to ACTIVATE when he ENTERS the FIELD to LOCK you into CANNOT SUMMON LINK-3 or Higher) ***Place the tokens in the zones away from the Links arrows. Linguriboh protects Wicckid from being negated by Trap cards like Infinite Impermanence. Against backrow matchups they are insane too. LINK-2 Cyberse Wicckid is an absurd card that is a fundamental piece for the deck to spin and you access the cards you need to make your turn 1 setup and even generate follow up on your opponent's turn by activating Superfactorial and bringing 1 of the Mathmech from gy in the zone it points to (it doesn't have to be the XYZ in Wicckid's zone to trigger its effect). COOL INTERACTION: WICCKID + SUPERFACTORIAL = You don't need to bring XYZ to the field in the Wicckid zone, but the Reborn of the GY is one in the Wicckid zone and even then you in the new chain link can use Wicckid cl1 Laplacian cl2. As long as Wicckid is on the field you can generate plus and add Mathmech Tuners to the hand every turn. Wicckid protecting the Cyberse he points out from Destruction is also absurd. See what is really going to banish from gy as cost of Wicckid because you don't want to banish Mathmech level 4 monsters and if possible you want to also keep the Links in gy so that your Accesscode has multiple pops so if you have XYZ Alembertian and Laplacian at GY banning them is always free. A very interesting play is to use Wicckid's absurd effect in your favor when you open it going second to force interactions because if you do Wicckid with eXceed in your hand, you practically get to Accesscode without losing to cards that destroy, that is, guaranteed to force interactions . It happens a lot to use I:P Masquerena to Accesscode on the opponent's turn in trap matches already to start your turn by destroying the opponent's backrow with an Accesscode of 4300atk that cannot be destroyed by effects. When opponent uses Dogmatika Maximus effect you always send I:P Masquerena + Unicorn to GY. (remember to keep a card in hand for Knightmare Unicorn - a very simple detail to remember for I:P Masquerena to work) One cool thing about this deck is the ability to Accesscode with a lot of extra effects like Attack twice or Doubled ATK which is really good.

deck_description: Dragon Link is a powerful combo deck that aims to go first and set up disruption, but can also OTK going second through its easy access to Borrelsword Dragon. It excels at playing through your opponent's disruption through the use of chain blocking. Your main starters are Black Metal Dragon, Starliege Seyfert, and Chaos Space. These cards can give you access to additional monsters while chain blocking your most important effects. For instance, if you have Black Metal Dragon and a Rokket monster in hand, you can use Black Metal Dragon to link summon Striker Dragon. Then, since both monsters' effects activate at the same time, you can decide what order they will occur in the chain. Your opponent will only be able to respond to the last card activated in the chain. By making Striker Dragon chain link 1 and Black Metal Dragon chain link 2, your opponent cannot use a card like Ash Blossom to negate your Striker Dragon's effect. Therefore, you can successfully add Boot Sector Launch and use it to summon the Rokket monster from hand. To play through interruption optimally, you will have to decide which effects to chain block based on what cards you have in hand and what situation you are in. Here are a few basic combos you can go through. #1 Black Metal Dragon Normal Summon Black Metal Dragon > Link Summon Striker Dragon > Activate Both Effects To Search Boot Sector Launch And Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon(RedMD) > Banish Striker Dragon To Special Summon RedMD > Activate RedMD's Effect To Special Summon Black Metal Dragon From Grave > Use RedMD And Black Metal Dragon To Link Summon Dragunity Knight Romulus And Activate The Effects Of Romulus And Black Metal Dragon To Add Dragon Ravine And Another RedMD > Activate Dragon Ravine And Discard 1 Card To Activate Its Effect To Send Absorouter Dragon To Grave > Activate Absorouter's Effect To Add Rokket Tracer > Activate Boot Sector Launch And Use Its Effect To Special Summon Rokket Tracer > Activate Rokket Tracer's Effect To Destroy Romulus And Special Summon Rokket Recharger Or Silverrokket From Deck > Synchro Summon Borreload Savage Dragon And Use Its Effect To Equip Romulus #2 Chaos Space + 1 Dark Monster Activate Chaos Space And Send A Dark From Hand To Grave To Search White Dragon Wyverburster > Banish The Dark Monster From Grave To Summon Wyverburster > Link Summon Striker Dragon And Activate Both Effects To Search Boot Sector And Black Dragon Collapserpent > Banish Wyverburster To Summon Collapserpent > At This Point You Can Activate The Effect Of Chaos Space In Grave To Place Wyverburster On The Bottom Of Your Deck And Draw 1 Card > Use Striker Dragon And Collapserpent To Link Summon Romulus And Activate The Effects Of Romulus And Collapserpent To Search Dragon Ravine And Wyverburster > Activate Dragon Ravine And Use Its Effect To Discard Wyverburster, Or Any Card In Hand That You Don't Need Or That You Want In Grave, And Send Absorouter To Grave > Activate Absorouter To Search Rokket Tracer > Activate Boot Sector Launch And Use Its Effect To Special Summon Rokket Tracer From Hand > Use Tracer's Effect To Destroy Romulus And Special Summon A Level 4 Rokket From Deck > Synchro Summon Borreload Savage Dragon And Equip Romulus *this can also be performed by using a light monster with chaos space to search collapserpent first *also note that this is performed without the use of your normal summon **you could also perform this combo with only starliege seyfert and 1 discard by using seyfert to search collapserpent, but it would use your normal summon and wouldn't get you the draw #3 Black Metal Dragon + Noctovision Dragon + 1 Rokket Monster Normal Summon Black Metal Dragon > Link Summon Striker Dragon > Activate The Effects Of Striker Dragon, Black Metal Dragon, And Noctovision Dragon To Search Boot Sector Launch, Search Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon, And Special Summon Noctovision From Hand > Banish Striker Dragon To Special Summon RedMD > Use RedMD's Effect To Special Summon Black Metal Dragon From Grave > Use Noctovision And Black Metal Dragon To Link Summon Romulus And Use The Effects Of Romulus, Black Metal Dragon, And Noctovision To Search Dragon Ravine, Search Another RedMD, And Draw 1 Card > Use RedMD And Romulus To Link Summon Hieratic Seal Of The Heavenly Spheres > Activate Dragon Ravine And Use Its Effect To Discard 1 And Send Absorouter To Grave > Activate Absorouter To Add Tracer Or Another Level 4 Rokket If Tracer Is Already In Hand > Activate Boot Sector And Use Its Effect To Special Summon Tracer And The Other Rokket Monster From Hand > Activate Tracer To Destroy Boot Sector And Special Summon Rokket Synchron From Deck > Use Tracer And The Level 4 Rokket To Synchro Summon Chaos Ruler, The Chaotic Magical Dragon And Use Its Effect To Excavate 5 And Add 1 Light Or Dark Monster Excavated To Hand Then Send The Remaining Cards To Grave (this Can Give You Access To Extra Monsters To Extend With, Thin Your Deck, And Setup Your Graveyard For Future Plays) > Use Chaos Ruler, The Chaotic Magical Dragon And Rokket Synchron To Synchro Summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss #4 Black Metal Dragon + Quick Launch + 1 Rokket Monster Normal Summon Black Metal Dragon > Link Summon Striker Dragon > Activate Both Effects To Search Boot Sector Launch And Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon > Banish Striker Dragon To Special Summon RedMD > Activate RedMD's Effect To Special Summon Black Metal Dragon From Graveyard > Use RedMD And Black Metal Dragon To Link Summon Hieratic Seal Of The Heavenly Spheres > Activate Black Metal Dragon To Search Another RedMD > Activate Boot Sector And Use Its Effect To Special Summon The Rokket Monster From Hand > Activate Quick Launch To Special Summon A Rokket Monster From Deck (if You Don't Yet Have Tracer, You Will Want To Summon It Here) > Use Tracer's Effect To Destroy Boot Sector And Summon Rokket Synchron From Deck (if You Started With Synchron In Hand, You Will Summon A Level 4 Rokket Here Instead) > Synchro Summon Chaos Ruler, The Chaotic Magical Dragon And Use Its Effect > Synchro Summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss #5 Black Metal Dragon + White Dragon Wyverburster + Rokket Tracer + Rokket Recharger Normal Summon Black Metal Dragon > Link Summon Striker Dragon > Activate Both Effects To Search Boot Sector Launch And Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon > Banish Black Metal Dragon To Summon Wyverburster > Use Striker Dragon And Wyverburster To Link Summon Hieratic Seal Of The Heavenly Spheres > Activate Wyverburster To Add Collapserpent > Banish Wyverburster To Summon Collapserpent > Use Collapserpent To Link Summon Another Striker Dragon And Place It In The Zone That Spheres Bottom Right Link Arrow Points To > Activate Collapserpent To Add Wyverburster > Activate Boot Sector And Use Its Effect To Special Summon Tracer And Recharger From Hand > Use Tracer To Link Summon Guardragon Pisty In The Zone That Spheres Bottom Left Link Arrow Points To > At This Point You Will Have Striker Dragon And Pisty Positioned To Both Point At The Same Zone, So You Can Use Pisty's Effect To Special Summon Tracer From Grave To That Zone > Banish Striker Dragon To Summon RedMD > Use RedMD To Summon The Striker Dragon That Is In Grave > Use RedMD, Striker Dragon, Pisty, And Recharger To Link Summon Saryuja And Activate Its Effect To Draw 4 Cards Then Return 3 Cards From Your Hand To The Bottom Of The Deck (by This Point You Will Have Thinned Out Your Deck A Good Bit So You Can Find Hand Traps And Board Breakers, And Setup Your Hand For Future Turns) > From Here You Can Use Tracer's Effect To Destroy Saryuja And Special Summon A Recharger Or Silverrokket From Deck > Synchro Summon Borreload Savage Dragon And Equip Saryuja These combos outlined should give you a basic idea of how the deck is played. Throughout your turn, you will ideally gain access to even more plays through the cards you draw and excavate. As you get more familiar with the deck, you will see many other combo lines that you can go through. The usual end board is spheres + hot red dragon archfiend abyss, spheres + borreload savage dragon, or sometimes all 3. Spheres functions as both disruption and a way to search levianeer by summoning brotaur off its second effect. By this point you will have already filled your graveyard with the necessary requirements to summon it when your opponent passes turn. It can then be used to help break the board they set up if they managed to play through your disruption. Some things to keep in mind: *Rokket Tracer's effect will lock you into summoning dark monsters from the extra deck for the rest of the turn. *Rokket Synchron's effect will lock you into summoning dark monsters from the extra deck for the rest of the turn. *Black Metal Dragon is not once per turn. *Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres can only activate its effect to return a card to hand while in an extra monster zone. *When tributing itself for cost, Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres can resolve its effect to return a card to hand while under skill drain, because it won't be on the field during resolution. *Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres does not target. You will choose which face-up card to return to hand when resolving its effect. *Nibiru will trigger Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres effect to special summon a dragon from deck. *Rokket Tracer's effect is a quick effect, so you can chain it to the activation of one of your spell cards, and destroy that spell card, to get both effects without having to sacrifice an additional resource. *White Dragon Wyverburster and Black Dragon Collapserpent's effect to special summon themselves from hand is once per turn, but their effect to add each other is not.

deck_description: (I don't know why it took me this long to submit a deck of my favorite deck of all time but oh well)  Have you ever played Pacifis control and thought "Man I wish I had bricks to keep the gameplay fresh"? Well look no further because Generaider is here (and has been for a while but let's not talk about that). This deck is one of those classic field spell centric decks that has zero way to play when the field spell is somewhere other than on board. But unlike those decks, you're running a huge amount of level 9s that really want to stay in deck for the deck to function. However, Generaiders have some extremely good support to make up for this inherent weak spot that makes them semi-consistent and an absolute king of the mid-game.  There are 9 main deck monsters in the archetype and really only 6 are worth talking about. Harr, Hela, Utgarda, and Nidhogg all have the usual Generaider effects where they tribute monsters for a beneficial effect. Harr is an omni-negate, Hela is a reborn, Utgarda is a targeting banish, and Nidhogg is a summon negate. Mardel and Loptr are a bit unique in the deck as Mardel is your search card when summoned and Loptr tributes any Generaider on board (including itself) for a level 9 Generaider from deck. Loptr is also the only normal summon in the deck, so all you Aleister fanboys can go wild. Naglfar, Frodi, and Dovelgus are all really really bleh compared to the rest, so don't run them unless you feel super confident in your ability to draw like Lithium when he plays Monarchs.  As for ratios of the main deck Generaiders, 3 Mardel and 3 Loptr is standard with one or two of the others depending on what you think you'll need in the deck. Trias Hierarchia is also a really good inclusion in the deck as it can tribute your Generaider tokens to summon itself on your opponent's turn. If you include that, run 2 or 3 copies as it is always online if you have access to the field spell.  Onto the spell cards, Boss Stage is the heart and soul of the deck. It kinda defines the whole playstyle of Generaiders, that being playing during your opponent's turn but in a cooler way than PSY-Frames could ever hope to achieve. It summons tokens during their turn that enable every Generaider to pop off, and it summons one from deck before doing so. Just the coolest field spell in the game in my opinion. Run three because you have to.  To find the field spell we have 7 additional backrow (plus Mardel) to find it. Terraforming is Terraforming and it just does Terraforming things. I'd run three if I could, but you kinda can't and probably never will be able to again. RIP in kill sweet prince. Boss Quest searches two Generaider spells and traps with different names for the low, low cost of putting a brick back in the deck. You run three and only ever three. Boss Fight activates Boss Stage from the deck or GY. It's like Metaverse but better. Run three. Boss Room is a really cool card that changes any activated effect into both players drawing one card. I usually run three, but with Boss Quest it's almost always accessible so you can run one or two instead.  The non-Generaider backrow is pretty self-explanatory. Pot of Avarice keeps you in the game longer than 11 turns which might not ever come up if the people you play against are always on combo decks, but I always end up playing against Dark Magician or Geist 90% of the time so it's nice to have this card in the deck. Kuji-Kiri Curse is an additional unbricking tool that also sets up Hela while drawing two cards. You can run Prosperity instead, but you do want your extra deck to help close out games. World Legacy's Monstrosity is an amazing card in the deck as it can either summon one level 9 from your hand or summon two from deck if you have one on board already. Other than just simply waiting for Boss Stage to activate a few times, this is how you get into the extra deck. Rank-Up Magic Argent Chaos Force is a bit of a sussy include, but I lost a game to geist while being 100 LP from winning, so this enables you to summon this deck's version of "Cowboy for game" being Number C9.  The extra deck is just every single good rank 9 you can run with some links to help with using Loptr as material when your deck is running low on cards. Heart-eartH is my favorite xyz monster in the game, and could absolutely be replaced by something better, but it's included here because I really like the card. Tachyon Dragon helps close out games with its skill drain effect. Enterblathnir is just really good answer to a lot of problem cards with its non-targeting banish. Dyson Sphere is good at cleaning up games by attacking directly (and then you can rank it up to really close out a game). Hyperyton brings even more negates to the party in the weirdest way possible. The Cat is another Hela but without the tribute cost. Jormungandr is technically the boss monster of the deck and can steal your opponent's resources to achieve big number.  The Knightmares are standard and don't need explaining. World Gears, however, is probably the worst deckbuilding choice I have ever made. If you summon this card, it clears the board, which sounds super cool. But Generaiders kinda want the board so they can build up advantage turn by turn and exhaust their opponent. Not to mention if you manage to get 3 level 9's on board, you can access the entire extra deck (except the chaos xyz cards) instead of a field nuke towers. It might be better than I make it out to be, but I've never had it work for me.  In the side deck, Lava Golem is a solid choice with how few normal summons the deck has. Kaijus might be better in most cases, but Enterblathnir can usually handle a single boss monster on its own. Raigeki is Raigeki and it's just better lightning storm now that it's unbanned. Cosmic Cyclone is a good answer to other spell reliant decks and Heavy Storm Duster does the same but while dodging Anti-Spell and Imperial Order (Not anymore though, get fucked IO). Imperm is just my favorite handtrap with how effective it is going first or second, but you can use any other hand traps you'd like.  This definitely isn't the best build of the deck out there, but I'm not a huge fan of mixing archetypes together so this is the best I can make while keeping it pure. You can add Girsu, Therizia, or Aleister and their engine cards to give the deck more normal summons and either extension or boss monsters, or use a Guru deck as the base and splash in Generaider if you're a streamer who's beyond high on copium. If you have any questions or suggestions, leave them below so I can try and improve the deck as best as I can.

deck_excerpt: Budgeted list for PUNK VW because i'm too poor for Halq/Auroradon and Baronne de Fleur
deck_description: By no means the most efficient thing to be doing with this engine. The P.U.N.K.'s are capable of going into things like Aurorodon lines and Baronne de Fleur, but I can't really afford that to a deck i'm taking to locals maybe once a month. That being said, they've got some fun synergies and I personally feel like VW can do more interesting things with the 2 slots missing from Desires and fill them with Small World lines. Amazing Dragon just cares about Psychics in Grave for it's bounce effect, not specifically P.U.N.K.'s.  First thing i would cut is the Sharakusai/Rising Carp for Halq setup.
